Part 6: The Master Pipeline (The API Endpoint)

    Python

        @app.post("/chat", response_model=SwarmResponse)
        async def chat_with_swarm(request: UserRequest):
            print(f"\n--- NEW REQUEST FROM [{request.user_id}] ---")

    What it implies: We open the front door. The async keyword allows multiple users to talk to the server at
                     the exact same time without blocking each other.

    -------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
    1. The @app.post("/chat") (The Mailroom Door)

            Imagine your entire Python file is a massive Corporate Headquarters.
            If a user on the internet wants to talk to your AI, they cannot just walk into the building and
            start wandering the halls. They have to go to a specific door.

            @ (The Python Decorator): This is a magic Python symbol that acts like a signpost.
            It tells the server, "Hey, pay attention to the function right below me!"

            app: This is the name of our FastAPI building.

            .post: In the internet world, there are different ways to send mail.

            A GET request means "I just want to read a webpage."

            A POST request means "I am handing you a heavy package of data, and I need you to do work on it."

            ("/chat"): This is the room number.

            Translation: @app.post("/chat") literally means: "Put a mailbox on the outside of the building
            labeled '/chat'. If a heavy package (POST) arrives at this mailbox, immediately hand it to the
            Python function sitting right below this sign."

        2. The request Variable (The Cardboard Box)

            Directly below that sign, we wrote this function:
            async def chat_with_swarm(request: UserRequest):

            When the user sends data from the internet (like from an iPhone app or Swagger UI),
            FastAPI automatically puts all their data into a cardboard box.

            request is just the name we gave to that cardboard box. It is not a magic Python word.
            We could have named it incoming_box or user_data or pizza_delivery. We just use request because
             it is standard engineering vocabulary for an "HTTP Request".

            : UserRequest is our strict Pydantic security guard. It looks at the box and says:
             "I will only let this box inside if it contains exactly two items: a user_id and a prompt."

        3. The Dot Notation: request.user_id (Opening the Box)

            Now the box is sitting on your desk inside the Python function. The box is named request.
            How do we open the box and pull out the specific items inside? We use Dot Notation (.).

            In Python, a dot . means "look inside."

            request.user_id means: "Look inside the box named request, and pull out the string labeled user_id."

            request.prompt means: "Look inside the box named request, and pull out the string labeled prompt."

            If the user sent the JSON payload:
            {"user_id": "Alex", "prompt": "Hello AI!"}

            Then in our Python code:

            request.user_id literally transforms into "Alex"

            request.prompt literally transforms into "Hello AI!"
